    The stack buffer overflow error occurs in the crc8 function, which is       
    called from main. The crash is happening due to a classic off-by-one error  
    in the loop condition.                                                      
                                                                                
    Let's analyze the code and program state:                                   
                                                                                
     1 In main, buf is declared as uint8_t buf[7] - this creates an array with  
       indices 0 through 6 (7 elements total).                                  
     2 The function crc8 is called with sizeof(buf) as the length argument,     
       which correctly evaluates to 7.                                          
     3 Inside crc8, the loop is: for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)              
        • len is 7                                                              
        • The loop condition is i <= len, so i goes from 0 to 7 (inclusive)     
        • When i = 7, the code accesses buf[7] - but buf only has indices 0-6   
        • This is an out-of-bounds memory access, causing the stack buffer      
          overflow                                                              
                                                                                
    The root cause is the loop condition i <= len in the crc8 function. Since   
    len represents the number of bytes in the buffer, the valid indices are 0   
    to (len - 1). The loop should iterate from i = 0 to i < len, not i <= len.  
                                                                                
    When i = 7, the code executes crc ^= buf[7], which accesses memory beyond   
    the allocated buffer, triggering the stack buffer overflow.                 
                                                                                
    The defect is in the loop condition in crc8. The current condition allows   
    access to the 8th byte (index 7) when only 7 bytes (indices 0-6) are        
    available.                                                                  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Change the loop condition in crc8 from i <= len to i < len to correctly  
       iterate over the valid indices of the buffer.                            
     2 The fix is simple and only affects the crc8 function:                    
                                                                                
        for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {                                      
                                                                                
       This change ensures we only access indices 0 through len-1, which is     
       exactly the range of valid indices for a buffer of length len.           
                                                                                
    This is both the minimal local fix and the thorough root-cause fix, as      
    there are no other issues in the code that contribute to this specific      
    buffer overflow.                                                            
                                                                                
